
Chapter 7 — Forecast Leakage
Why Forecasts Become Inaccurate

Every quarter begins with optimism.

The pipeline looks healthy.

Sales targets feel achievable.

Leadership gains confidence from the forecast.

Then reality unfolds.

Deals expected to close get pushed to next month.

Large opportunities disappear.

Revenue misses the target.

The question becomes:

"What went wrong?"

Most of the time, nothing changed overnight.

The forecast was simply built on assumptions instead of evidence.

This is Forecast Leakage.

What is Forecast Leakage?

Forecast Leakage occurs when projected revenue no longer reflects the actual health of the pipeline.

Deals appear likely to close.

In reality, they lack the momentum, engagement, or buying signals needed to reach the finish line.

The forecast becomes a reflection of hope rather than probability.

